{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Seq2Seq Pretraining Is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Sequence-to-sequence (Seq2Seq) pretraining trains an encoder–decoder transformer to reconstruct a corrupted or translated version of its input. The encoder reads the input with "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "full bidirectional attention"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", building rich contextual representations. The decoder then generates the target sequence token-by-token, attending to both its own previous outputs (via causal self-attention) and the encoder's hidden states (via cross-attention)."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Unlike causal LM (decoder-only) or masked LM (encoder-only), Seq2Seq pretraining produces a model that can both understand and generate — making it the natural fit for translation, summarisation, and structured prediction tasks."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Seq2Seq pretraining: encoder reads input bidirectionally, decoder generates target with cross-attention; T5 span corruption and BART text infilling objectives"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Encoder–Decoder Architecture"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The canonical architecture has three types of attention:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Encoder self-attention"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": full bidirectional — every encoder token attends to every other encoder token."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Decoder self-attention"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": causal (lower-triangular mask) — each decoder token only sees previous decoder tokens, preserving autoregressive generation."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Cross-attention"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": decoder queries attend to encoder keys and values — this is how the decoder reads the input."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nclass CrossAttention(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"Decoder cross-attention: Q from decoder, K/V from encoder.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, d_model, num_heads):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.q_proj = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.k_proj = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.v_proj = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.out    = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model)\n        self.scale  = (d_model // num_heads) ** -0.5\n        self.heads  = num_heads\n        self.d_head = d_model // num_heads\n\n    def forward(self, decoder_hidden, encoder_hidden):\n        # decoder_hidden: (B, T_dec, d_model)\n        # encoder_hidden: (B, T_enc, d_model)\n        B = decoder_hidden.size(0)\n\n        def split(x): return x.view(B, -1, self.heads, self.d_head).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        Q = split(self.q_proj(decoder_hidden))    # (B, H, T_dec, d_head)\n        K = split(self.k_proj(encoder_hidden))    # (B, H, T_enc, d_head)\n        V = split(self.v_proj(encoder_hidden))    # (B, H, T_enc, d_head)\n\n        # No mask here — decoder can attend to ALL encoder positions\n        scores = (Q @ K.transpose(-2, -1)) * self.scale   # (B, H, T_dec, T_enc)\n        attn   = torch.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\n        out    = (attn @ V).transpose(1, 2).reshape(B, -1, self.heads * self.d_head)\n        return self.out(out)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Training Loss"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Seq2Seq models are trained with cross-entropy on the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "decoder output tokens only"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". The encoder input is not predicted — it is consumed as context."}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\mathcal{L}(\\theta) = -\\frac{1}{|T_{\\text{dec}}|} \\sum_{t=1}^{|T_{\\text{dec}}|} \\log P(y_t \\mid y_{<t},\\, \\text{Encoder}(x);\\, \\theta)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Teacher forcing is used during training: the decoder receives ground-truth target tokens as its inputs at each step, rather than its own previous predictions."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5: Text-to-Text Transfer Transformer"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5 (Raffel et al. 2020) introduced a unified "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "text-to-text framework"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": every NLP task is expressed as a string-in, string-out problem. For pretraining, T5 uses a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "span corruption"}, {"type": "text", "text": " objective:"}]}, {"type": "orderedList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Sample 15% of tokens to mask, grouping consecutive selected tokens into spans."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Replace each span with a unique sentinel token ("}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "<extra_id_0>"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "<extra_id_1>"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", …)."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The decoder's target is: each sentinel followed by the tokens it replaced, ending with "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "<eos>"}, {"type": "text", "text": "."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# T5 span corruption — illustrative implementation\nimport random\n\ndef t5_corrupt(tokens, mask_prob=0.15, mean_span=3):\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns (encoder_input, decoder_target) as token lists.\n    Sentinels are represented as strings '<extra_id_N>'.\n    \"\"\"\n    spans, i, n = [], 0, 0\n    selected = set()\n\n    while i < len(tokens):\n        if random.random() < mask_prob:\n            span_len = max(1, round(random.gauss(mean_span, 1)))\n            selected.update(range(i, min(i + span_len, len(tokens))))\n            i += span_len\n        else:\n            i += 1\n\n    # Build encoder input (corrupted)\n    enc, dec = [], []\n    span_id, in_span = 0, False\n    for j, tok in enumerate(tokens):\n        if j in selected:\n            if not in_span:\n                sentinel = f'<extra_id_{span_id}>'\n                enc.append(sentinel)\n                dec.append(sentinel)\n                span_id += 1\n                in_span = True\n            dec.append(tok)\n        else:\n            enc.append(tok)\n            in_span = False\n\n    dec.append('<eos>')\n    return enc, dec\n\n\ntokens = ['The', 'quick', 'brown', 'fox', 'jumps', 'over', 'the', 'lazy', 'dog']\nenc, dec = t5_corrupt(tokens, mask_prob=0.3, mean_span=2)\nprint('enc:', enc)   # e.g. ['The', '<extra_id_0>', 'fox', '<extra_id_1>', 'dog']\nprint('dec:', dec)   # e.g. ['<extra_id_0>', 'quick', 'brown', '<extra_id_1>', 'jumps', 'over', 'the', 'lazy', '<eos>']"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Span corruption is more efficient than token-level masking: replacing a 3-token span with a single sentinel shortens the encoder input, reducing the number of self-attention operations without reducing the number of supervision signals."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BART: Denoising with Text Infilling"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BART (Lewis et al. 2020) pretrains by corrupting the input text with several "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "noise functions"}, {"type": "text", "text": " and then training the decoder to reconstruct the original uncorrupted text. The key difference from T5 is that BART's decoder always targets the full original document, not just the corrupted spans."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BART's primary noise function is "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "text infilling"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": a single "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "[MASK]"}, {"type": "text", "text": " token replaces a span of 0 or more tokens (drawn from a Poisson distribution with λ=3). This forces the model to learn to count — it must figure out how many tokens were removed, not just which one."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from transformers import BartTokenizer, BartForConditionalGeneration\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = BartTokenizer.from_pretrained('facebook/bart-base')\nmodel     = BartForConditionalGeneration.from_pretrained('facebook/bart-base')\n\n# BART denoising: encoder sees corrupted input, decoder generates original\ncorrupted = \"The <mask> jumped over the lazy dog.\"\noriginal  = \"The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy dog.\"\n\nenc_ids = tokenizer(corrupted, return_tensors='pt').input_ids\ndec_ids = tokenizer(original,  return_tensors='pt').input_ids\n\n# Shift decoder input right (prepend BOS, strip last token)\ndec_input = model.shift_tokens_right(\n    dec_ids, model.config.pad_token_id, model.config.decoder_start_token_id\n)\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    outputs = model(input_ids=enc_ids, decoder_input_ids=dec_input, labels=dec_ids)\n    print(f'Loss: {outputs.loss.item():.3f}')\n\n# Generation from a prompt\ngenerated = model.generate(enc_ids, max_new_tokens=20, num_beams=4)\nprint(tokenizer.decode(generated[0], skip_special_tokens=True))\n# → \"The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy dog.\""}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5 vs BART vs Standard Seq2Seq"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Property"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BART"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Standard Seq2Seq"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Pretraining objective"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Span corruption (sentinels)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Text infilling + permutation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Parallel bilingual sentence pairs"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Decoder target"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Sentinels + removed spans"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Full original document"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Target-language sentence"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Encoder input length"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Shorter (spans collapsed)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Same length as original"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Source-language length"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Best for"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Unified task framing, QA, NLU"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Summarisation, dialogue, generation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Machine translation"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key models"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5, mT5, Flan-T5, UL2"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BART, mBART, PEGASUS"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "MarianMT, Helsinki-NLP"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Using Flan-T5 for Text-to-Text Tasks"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Flan-T5 fine-tunes T5 on thousands of prompted tasks, making it directly usable for many tasks without further fine-tuning:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from transformers import T5ForConditionalGeneration, T5Tokenizer\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = T5Tokenizer.from_pretrained('google/flan-t5-base')\nmodel     = T5ForConditionalGeneration.from_pretrained('google/flan-t5-base')\nmodel.eval()\n\ndef t5_generate(prompt: str, max_new_tokens=64) -> str:\n    inputs = tokenizer(prompt, return_tensors='pt')\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        output_ids = model.generate(\n            **inputs,\n            max_new_tokens=max_new_tokens,\n            num_beams=4,\n            early_stopping=True\n        )\n    return tokenizer.decode(output_ids[0], skip_special_tokens=True)\n\n# Translation\nprint(t5_generate('translate English to French: The cat sat on the mat.'))\n# → 'Le chat s\\'est assis sur le tapis.'\n\n# Summarisation\nprint(t5_generate('summarize: The encoder reads the full input bidirectionally, building rich representations that the decoder can attend to via cross-attention while generating the output token by token.'))\n# → 'The encoder reads the input bidirectionally and the decoder generates the output via cross-attention.'\n\n# QA\nprint(t5_generate('question: What does the encoder do? context: The encoder reads input bidirectionally.'))\n# → 'reads input bidirectionally'"}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "The unifying insight of T5: "}, {"type": "text", "text": "if you frame every task as text-in → text-out, you need only one architecture, one pretraining objective, and one fine-tuning recipe. Translation, summarisation, classification, QA, and entity extraction all become the same kind of problem — generate the right string given the right prompt."}]}]}]}}